# Coding Guidelines
- Write clear, self-documenting functions with descriptive names; keep them small and single-purpose.
- Docstrings are optional; add them only for non-obvious behavior, public APIs that need contracts, or complex edge cases.
- Keep comments minimal; use them only for intent or decisions that code cannot show clearly.
- Prefer type hints everywhere; avoid `Any`; use `TypedDict`, `Protocol`, and `Enum` to clarify data shapes.
- Avoid mutable defaults; favor immutability where practical (e.g., `frozen` dataclasses) and isolate side effects to boundaries.
- Handle errors explicitly with precise exception types and actionable messages; avoid blanket `except`.
- Use context managers for resources (files, network clients, locks) to prevent leaks.
- Keep modules and functions short; extract helpers instead of deep nesting; maintain clear dependency direction.
- Use logging over `print`; choose appropriate log levels for signal vs noise.
- Write focused, deterministic tests alongside changes, covering edge cases and error paths.
- Use absolute imports.
- Validate data at system boundaries using Pydantic models; fail fast with clear validation errors on external inputs (APIs, files, user data).
- Prioritize clarity over premature optimization; profile before optimizing hot paths; document performance-critical sections and trade-offs.
